Descriptive Statistics Heatmap

This block generates a heatmap summarizing descriptive statistics and potential outliers for all numeric variables.

Function Summary analyze_dataframe

This helper inspects any numeric DataFrame:

  1. Calculates descriptive stats (mean, quartiles, IQR).
  2. Flags outliers beyond 1.5IQR.
  3. Plots a bluescale heatmap so patterns jump out visually.
  4. Optionally shows a correlation matrix. It returns the stats table when return_summary=True, feeding both human insight and downstream logic.

Inference Statistics

Summarize Activity vs. Insulin

This block calculates how insulin levels differ between participants who meet the activity goal and those who do not.

Function Summary summarize_activity_vs_insulin

Given total weekly minutes and insulin values, the function:

  1. Flags each participant as Meets_Goal (150min) or not.
  2. Computes the percentage meeting the goal.
  3. Calculates mean insulin for each group and the (above below). The resulting dictionary feeds the annotation in the scatter plot, translating raw numbers into a clear health impact story.
{'percent_above': np.float64(73.86), 'percent_below': np.float64(26.14), 'mean_insulin_above': np.float64(10.95), 'mean_insulin_below': np.float64(13.52), 'delta_insulin': np.float64(-2.57)}

Step 2: Feature Engineering

Creating a SPLOM to understand general trends in data

Pairwise Relationships (SPLOM)

This block plots pairwise relationships among biomarkers and activity metrics, colored by gender.

What this visual shows and why it matters
The scatterplot matrix (SPLOM) presents pairwise relationships among insulin, glucose, glycohemoglobin, activity metrics, and gender.

  • Offdiagonal scatter points show the direction (positive/negative) and strength of relationships.
  • Diagonal KDE curves summarise each variables distribution.
  • Hue by gender uncovers potential sexspecific trends.

How it helps the analysis
It visually tests linearity assumptions and hints at where strong associations (e.g., activity vs. insulin) might exist, guiding feature selection for later models.

Heatmap to check correlations

Correlation Matrix

This block visualizes correlations between activity measures and biomarkers.

What this visual shows and why it matters
This correlation heatmap displays Pearson correlations between all biomarkers and activity variables.

  • Deep blue or green = strong positive correlation; pale shades = weak/no correlation; yellow = negative.
  • Uppertriangle masking keeps the plot uncluttered.

How it helps the analysis
It pinpoints which biomarkers move together or in opposition, identifying candidates for multicollinearity checks and giving insight into potential causal pathways (e.g., sedentary time vs. CRP).

Overlay Goal Line & Annotate in Matplotlib

What this visual shows and why it matters
This scatter plot demonstrates the relationship between weekly activity minutes and fasting insulin.

  • Red dashed line = WHO guideline of 150min/week.
  • Gray dotted line = 97thpercentile cap to reduce extreme points.
  • Color groups instantly split participants meeting and not meeting the goal.
  • The annotation box quantifies percent above/below goal and the insulin delta.

How it helps the analysis
It directly answers the research question: Does meeting 150min/week associate with lower insulin? The downward trend and insulin quantify the benefit of regular activity.

Descriptions Section

Relevance to Human Health

Understanding how physical activity influences key biomarkers is critical for promoting longterm health. These markers are directly linked to chronic diseases such as:

  • Type 2 Diabetes
  • Cardiovascular Disease
  • Metabolic Syndrome
  • Obesityrelated Inflammation

Impact of Physical Activity on Biomarkers

  1. Insulin (U/mL)

    • Effect: Improves insulin sensitivity
    • Outcome: Lower circulating insulin levels; reduced risk of insulin resistance and type2diabetes

  2. Fasting Glucose (mg/dL) & HbA1c (%)

    • Effect: Enhances muscle glucose uptake
    • Outcome: Better blood glucose control; lower HbA1c values

  3. Cholesterol (HDL & Total)

    • Effect: Increases HDL (good cholesterol); may reduce LDL and total cholesterol
    • Outcome: Improved heart health; reduced cardiovascular risk

  4. CReactive Protein (CRP)

    • Effect: Decreases systemic inflammation
    • Outcome: Lower CRP levels; protection against chronic diseases and improved immune function

  5. Sedentary Time

    • Effect: Excessive sedentary behavior correlates with elevated insulin, worse lipid profiles, and higher CRP
    • Outcome: Provides a clear contrast between active and inactive lifestyles

Market Analysis Layer

  • 96million U.S. adults are prediabetic Source: CDC 2022 National Diabetes Statistics Report

  • 30% adoption of activity nudges (e.g., walking prompts, step goals) From digital health app engagement studies (JAMA, Nature Digital Medicine)

  • ~5% reduction in fasting insulin is associated with reduced diabetes risk Clinical studies suggest even modest increases in physical activity improve insulin sensitivity

  • Assumption: We reach 1million preventable cases long term

  • Annual direct medical cost of diabetes: ~$9,600 per person Source: ADA, 2022 Cost of Diabetes Report

  • Estimated cost savings:

    • 1million cases $8,000$10,000 per person=$8$10billion/year Source: ADA, 2022 Cost of Diabetes Report
